conomy and the Moral Economy, 1926–50 -- t15. The Quality of Charity, Values, and Entitlements, 1908–50 -- t16. Redundancy and Status-Class: Purveying Values through Recreation and Education, 1929–50 -- t17. ‘And the Church Preached Its View’ -- t18. ‘We Had a Live Union Then’ -- t19. ‘Much Wants More’: Framing the Politics of Labour -- t20. Inside the Frame: The Politics of Mediation -- t21. Organizing Labour in the 1940s: The Politics of Combination -- t22. Reproducing the Political Regime and Regimen, 1940–50 -- tPart V: Conclusions: Political Economy and Culture, 1800–1950 -- t23. Theory, Concept, and Text: A Holistic Approach to the Politics of Class -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn An Irish Working Class, Marilyn Silverman explores the dynamics of capitalism, colonialism, and state formation through an examination of the political economy and culture of those who contributed their labour. Stemming from the author's academic research on Ireland for over two decades, the book combines archival data, interviews, and participant observation to create a unique and intricate study of labourers' lives in Thomastown, County Kilkenny, between 1800 and 1950. Political anthropology, Gramscian approaches to hegemony, and the work of social historians on class experience all inform Silverman's perspective in this volume.Silverman explores the complex and changing consciousness, politics, and social relations of a cross-section of workers. These workers were employed in the mills, tanneries, artisanal shops, and retail outlets, and on the landed estates, farms, and public works projects which typified this highly differentiated locality. In constructing the social history of workers in a particular place over time, An Irish Working Class makes an important contribution to Irish Studies, European historical ethnography, and the anthropology of working-class life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aWorking classzIrelandzThomastown (Kilkenny)xHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classzIrelandzThomastown (Kilkenny)xHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144267079240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442670792423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442670792.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK